lectual practices of early modern authors, as well as early capitalist economic organization. With its probing look at the origins of modern copyright, The Author's Due will prove to be a watershed for historians, literary critics, and legal scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthorshipxHistory. 0aBook industries and tradexLaw and legislationzEnglandxHistory. 0aBook industries and tradezEnglandxHistory. 0aCopyrightzEnglandxHistory. 0aIntellectual propertyzEnglandxHistory. 0aPrinting industryxLaw and legislationzEnglandxHistory. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistory. 0aPublishing. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226490410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226490410.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles